      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown and build",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the {{lardons}} in a wide pan over medium heat until the fat renders. Remove and add to the slow cooker. Increase the heat to high. Season the {{chicken-thigh}} with {{sea-salt-fine}} and {{black-pepper}} and brown skin-side down for 4 minutes without moving, then flip for 2 minutes. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{onion}} to the pan and fry for 2 minutes. Add the {{garlic}} and {{tomato-puree}} and cook for 1 minute. Pour in the {{red-wine}} and scrape up all the browned bits. Add the {{stock-chicken}} and bring to a simmer. Pour over the chicken. Tuck in the {{thyme-fresh}} and {{bay-leaves}}. Cook on low for 6 to 8 hours.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the mushrooms",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "In the last 30 minutes, fry the {{mushrooms-chestnut}} in the {{unsalted-butter}} over high heat until browned. Stir into the slow cooker. Remove the {{thyme-fresh}} sprigs and {{bay-leaves}} before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Always bring the wine to a boil and deglaze the pan thoroughly. Raw wine added directly to the slow cooker stays sharp over the cook time",
              "cause": "Wine not reduced before the slow cooker, or not enough fond",
              "symptom": "Sauce thin and wine-forward rather than rounded"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Always fry mushrooms in butter over high heat before adding. Raw mushrooms release too much water in the slow cooker and lose all texture",
              "cause": "Added raw rather than browned first",
              "symptom": "Mushrooms soft and waterlogged"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the thighs 10 minutes before serving and place under a hot grill, skin-side up, for 5 minutes. The skin crisps quickly under direct heat",
              "cause": "Slow cooker produces steam rather than dry heat",
              "symptom": "Chicken skin pale and flabby"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Coq au vin is a weekend dinner rather than a weeknight dish, the prep requires 30 minutes of active work. The slow cooker then handles the braise without any attention for six to eight hours, producing a result that would otherwise need 90 minutes of stovetop supervision. Serve on mashed potato with the sauce spooned generously over.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
